List manipulation functions that automatically create and free nodes

 Pushes data onto the end of a list.

 Pushes data onto the beginning of a list.

 Pops data off the front of a list.

Detailed Description

These functions allocate or free memory every time they are called, and should be avoided if you are doing something such as popping a value off a list in order to push it onto a second list. Use the node functions instead.

Function Documentation

void* list_pop ( list *  haystack  ) 

Pops data off the end of a list.

Parameters:
[in] haystack The list from which the data is taken
Returns:
The pointer to the data on the last element of the list, or NULL when there are no list members left
This function automatically frees the list_node that held the data, but you are responsible for freeing the data.
